WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.619 --> 00:00:03.202
(chiming tone)

2
00:00:08.460 --> 00:00:09.330
<v Moderator>Joe is back,</v>

3
00:00:09.330 --> 00:00:13.980
and we're gonna turn our attention in this next presentation

4
00:00:13.980 --> 00:00:17.910
on issues related to musculoskeletal health

5
00:00:17.910 --> 00:00:20.310
as we look at some issues related specifically

6
00:00:20.310 --> 00:00:21.240
to sports medicine.

7
00:00:21.240 --> 00:00:22.980
Thank you, Joe. Take it away, sir.

8
00:00:22.980 --> 00:00:27.640
<v ->We're gonna move through really a bulk of medical issues</v>

9
00:00:28.680 --> 00:00:31.800
that are related to sports medicine and athlete

10
00:00:31.800 --> 00:00:33.660
that you need to be aware of,

11
00:00:33.660 --> 00:00:38.230
and a few musculoskeletal issues in this section.

12
00:00:39.870 --> 00:00:41.970
So let's get started right away.

13
00:00:41.970 --> 00:00:43.950
You have the preparticipation exam.

14
00:00:43.950 --> 00:00:46.650
That's where we start in sports medicine.

15
00:00:46.650 --> 00:00:49.140
You know what the primary objectives are.

16
00:00:49.140 --> 00:00:51.570
We wanna screen individuals

17
00:00:51.570 --> 00:00:55.266
for factors that may predispose them

18
00:00:55.266 --> 00:00:58.740
or be life-threatening or disabling to them.

19
00:00:58.740 --> 00:01:03.114
Pay attention to the fact that the AMA has called out twice

20
00:01:03.114 --> 00:01:06.420
for us to use the preparticipation exam

21
00:01:06.420 --> 00:01:09.157
since these are primarily healthy kids

22
00:01:09.157 --> 00:01:12.780
to have discussions about health related topics,

23
00:01:12.780 --> 00:01:16.110
particularly risk taking behaviors,

24
00:01:16.110 --> 00:01:20.070
smoking, drinking, drugs, sex, okay?

25
00:01:20.070 --> 00:01:25.070
So that has shown up repeatedly on the exam,

26
00:01:25.317 --> 00:01:30.317
the AMA's call to us to utilize the preparticipation exam

27
00:01:30.520 --> 00:01:32.130
in this manner.

28
00:01:32.130 --> 00:01:34.258
When we look at the preparticipation exam,

29
00:01:34.258 --> 00:01:38.250
we restrict athletes for certain reasons.

30
00:01:38.250 --> 00:01:41.760
A little over half of those are for musculoskeletal reasons.

31
00:01:41.760 --> 00:01:44.670
A little under half are for medical reasons.

32
00:01:44.670 --> 00:01:47.250
The greatest bulk of medical reasons

33
00:01:47.250 --> 00:01:52.050
are due to cardiovascular related issues.

34
00:01:52.050 --> 00:01:53.670
Elevated blood pressure

35
00:01:53.670 --> 00:01:57.060
is the most common cardiovascular abnormality

36
00:01:57.060 --> 00:02:00.300
found on the preparticipation exam.

37
00:02:00.300 --> 00:02:05.300
I'm going to give you, as I have, lots of most common.

38
00:02:06.030 --> 00:02:07.590
Those are things that I really want you

39
00:02:07.590 --> 00:02:11.493
to remember over the course of this.

40
00:02:12.840 --> 00:02:15.990
So what does Choosing Wisely tell us?

41
00:02:15.990 --> 00:02:20.940
Don't screen for testicular cancer or inguinal hernias

42
00:02:20.940 --> 00:02:25.860
in asymptomatic adolescent or adult patients, okay?

43
00:02:25.860 --> 00:02:30.180
That answers a question that I'm commonly asked about.

44
00:02:30.180 --> 00:02:32.010
And here are your clinical recommendations

45
00:02:32.010 --> 00:02:34.260
for the preparticipation exam.

46
00:02:34.260 --> 00:02:37.860
We're gonna talk about number one in a little more detail.

47
00:02:37.860 --> 00:02:41.651
How do we screen for cardiovascular disease

48
00:02:41.651 --> 00:02:46.651
and that risk for cardiac sudden death,

49
00:02:48.210 --> 00:02:51.339
or CSD as we refer to it.

50
00:02:51.339 --> 00:02:55.410
Athletes who have blood pressures under 160/100

51
00:02:55.410 --> 00:02:56.850
should not be restricted.

52
00:02:56.850 --> 00:02:58.413
Let them go on and play.

53
00:02:59.520 --> 00:03:04.520
We start that the activity alone is partial treatment

54
00:03:04.530 --> 00:03:07.260
for their elevated blood pressure,

55
00:03:07.260 --> 00:03:09.510
or their hypertension as it may be,

56
00:03:09.510 --> 00:03:13.830
but we can work that up as they are participating.

57
00:03:13.830 --> 00:03:16.928
Also, individuals who have well-controlled asthma,

58
00:03:16.928 --> 00:03:21.000
they can participate without any restriction.

59
00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:25.750
And lastly, for our general high school athletes

60
00:03:26.700 --> 00:03:28.530
outside of the NCAA,

61
00:03:28.530 --> 00:03:32.190
outside of Olympic or pre-Olympic sports

62
00:03:32.190 --> 00:03:34.972
or private organizations,

63
00:03:34.972 --> 00:03:39.972
there are no screening blood or urine tests for individuals,

64
00:03:40.230 --> 00:03:42.690
for asymptomatic individuals.

65
00:03:42.690 --> 00:03:44.700
So if you're asked about a screening test,

66
00:03:44.700 --> 00:03:48.010
no, we don't utilize screening tests

67
00:03:48.010 --> 00:03:52.140
simply because they're getting a preparticipation exam.

68
00:03:52.140 --> 00:03:54.390
So here's the next big question.

69
00:03:54.390 --> 00:03:56.806
Do I obtain a screening ECG

70
00:03:56.806 --> 00:04:01.383
for athletes undergoing their preparticipation exam?

71
00:04:02.250 --> 00:04:05.943
How many say yes? How many say no?

72
00:04:06.870 --> 00:04:08.640
Okay, well, this'll be fast then.

73
00:04:08.640 --> 00:04:10.620
Let's jump through this, right?

74
00:04:10.620 --> 00:04:14.280
We use the 14-point American Heart Association scale

75
00:04:14.280 --> 00:04:17.280
that covers some personal history, some family history,

76
00:04:17.280 --> 00:04:18.960
and then our physical exam.

77
00:04:18.960 --> 00:04:21.050
Those are the 14 points.

78
00:04:21.050 --> 00:04:25.293
I do not get a screening ECG, not in the United States.

79
00:04:26.253 --> 00:04:28.648
If I have a positive response

80
00:04:28.648 --> 00:04:32.070
anywhere on the 14-point checklist,

81
00:04:32.070 --> 00:04:33.556
then it's up to my discretion

82
00:04:33.556 --> 00:04:36.960
as to whether or not I want to obtain an ECG.

83
00:04:36.960 --> 00:04:38.287
That's the answer.

84
00:04:38.287 --> 00:04:40.440
Now, where do I find

85
00:04:40.440 --> 00:04:43.410
this 14-point American Heart Association checklist?

86
00:04:43.410 --> 00:04:47.520
Because I don't keep it every time a student comes in

87
00:04:47.520 --> 00:04:48.960
for a preparticipation exam.

88
00:04:48.960 --> 00:04:50.370
I don't know where it is.

89
00:04:50.370 --> 00:04:53.209
Well, if you're using the form,

90
00:04:53.209 --> 00:04:57.600
and most states have utilized this form,

91
00:04:57.600 --> 00:05:00.663
they just put it in a different format, but it's all there.

92
00:05:02.400 --> 00:05:04.980
This is available. It's free for download.

93
00:05:04.980 --> 00:05:06.720
You can get it from the AAFP,

94
00:05:06.720 --> 00:05:08.850
you can get it from American Academy of Pediatrics,

95
00:05:08.850 --> 00:05:10.980
you can get it from American College of Sports Medicine,

96
00:05:10.980 --> 00:05:12.540
et cetera, et cetera.

97
00:05:12.540 --> 00:05:17.100
And so here are my health history questions

98
00:05:17.100 --> 00:05:18.243
about the athlete,

99
00:05:19.380 --> 00:05:23.490
and here are my health history questions about the family.

100
00:05:23.490 --> 00:05:25.410
And then I have my physical exam.

101
00:05:25.410 --> 00:05:27.390
What's my blood pressure, do I have a heart murmur?

102
00:05:27.390 --> 00:05:28.260
Et cetera, et cetera.

103
00:05:28.260 --> 00:05:32.190
So there are my 14-point checklist

104
00:05:32.190 --> 00:05:33.750
right there on your form.

105
00:05:33.750 --> 00:05:36.150
You just have to know where to look for it.

106
00:05:36.150 --> 00:05:39.813
And it's not labeled as such, but it's all right there.

107
00:05:40.830 --> 00:05:42.603
Okay, so our first question,

108
00:05:43.517 --> 00:05:47.400
examination findings of a 17-year-old male athlete

109
00:05:47.400 --> 00:05:48.570
with near syncope

110
00:05:48.570 --> 00:05:51.270
and suspicion for hypertrophic cardiomyopathy

111
00:05:51.270 --> 00:05:53.553
would include which of the following?

112
00:05:59.190 --> 00:06:00.400
Here we go. Great.

113
00:06:00.400 --> 00:06:01.680
So most of you got this.

114
00:06:01.680 --> 00:06:04.650
This is a crescendo-decrescendo systolic murmur,

115
00:06:04.650 --> 00:06:09.630
left sternal border, that increases with Valsalva.

116
00:06:09.630 --> 00:06:12.090
So we look at cardiac sudden death in young athletes,

117
00:06:12.090 --> 00:06:13.440
and so what I wanted to do

118
00:06:13.440 --> 00:06:16.470
is give you a big picture here first.

119
00:06:16.470 --> 00:06:20.220
What's the biggest cause of death in these individuals?

120
00:06:20.220 --> 00:06:21.510
Well, they're accidents.

121
00:06:21.510 --> 00:06:24.060
That's the number one cause of death.

122
00:06:24.060 --> 00:06:28.080
And then what's the number two cause of death in athletes?

123
00:06:28.080 --> 00:06:31.410
Cardiac related issues, okay?

124
00:06:31.410 --> 00:06:35.220
And then we get suicide, so mental health issues

125
00:06:35.220 --> 00:06:37.230
that are gonna follow right after that.

126
00:06:37.230 --> 00:06:40.350
So this is 2023 data.

127
00:06:40.350 --> 00:06:44.580
It's as hot off the press as it can be.

128
00:06:44.580 --> 00:06:49.580
When we look at actual heart-related causes,

129
00:06:50.430 --> 00:06:54.930
hypertrophic cardiomyopathy jumps right to the top.

130
00:06:54.930 --> 00:06:59.700
So this table deserves a little bit of an explanation,

131
00:06:59.700 --> 00:07:03.390
because Barry Maron's work in the first column

132
00:07:03.390 --> 00:07:08.100
looked only at sudden death in athletes,

133
00:07:08.100 --> 00:07:09.810
cardiac-related issues.

134
00:07:09.810 --> 00:07:14.415
A third of those were due to hypertrophic cardiomyopathy,

135
00:07:14.415 --> 00:07:16.660
the greatest portion

136
00:07:17.640 --> 00:07:20.010
And Petex's data,

137
00:07:20.010 --> 00:07:23.640
they looked at all causes of death in athletes.

138
00:07:23.640 --> 00:07:26.220
And so hypertrophic cardiomyopathy,

139
00:07:26.220 --> 00:07:31.220
because accidents are so high, fell in terms of percentage.

140
00:07:32.280 --> 00:07:37.280
Know this: male sex, Black race, and a basketball player

141
00:07:39.990 --> 00:07:43.710
is my highest risk for cardiac sudden death.

142
00:07:43.710 --> 00:07:46.263
Know that, okay?

143
00:07:47.940 --> 00:07:51.463
All right, and so hypertrophic cardiomyopathy,

144
00:07:51.463 --> 00:07:54.840
autosomal dominant, but it has variable penetrance,

145
00:07:54.840 --> 00:07:59.490
meaning I might not display all of the characteristics

146
00:07:59.490 --> 00:08:00.323
right now.

147
00:08:00.323 --> 00:08:03.810
They may develop over time, which is why,

148
00:08:03.810 --> 00:08:07.727
because I had a screening test and an echocardiogram at 16,

149
00:08:07.727 --> 00:08:11.460
I don't need to be concerned about it at 18.

150
00:08:11.460 --> 00:08:15.630
I may have to consider a full workup again

151
00:08:15.630 --> 00:08:17.970
because of that variable penetrance.

152
00:08:17.970 --> 00:08:21.027
I might not have met the criteria at 16,

153
00:08:21.027 --> 00:08:24.990
but between 16 and 18, or 19 or 20,

154
00:08:24.990 --> 00:08:29.100
I may develop a full-blown hypertrophic cardiomyopathy.

155
00:08:29.100 --> 00:08:32.590
So we have to pay attention to that, okay?

156
00:08:32.590 --> 00:08:36.930
That's sort of a truism in this condition.

157
00:08:36.930 --> 00:08:41.280
so I can't say it's been evaluated once I'm done.

158
00:08:41.280 --> 00:08:45.390
If I'm suspicious of it, if I have physical findings of it,

159
00:08:45.390 --> 00:08:48.000
I need to reevaluate.

160
00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:51.648
Imaging or diagnosis can be done via echocardiogram.

161
00:08:51.648 --> 00:08:55.410
You need to let the cardiologist know

162
00:08:55.410 --> 00:08:57.210
that you're looking for this

163
00:08:57.210 --> 00:08:59.670
so that they can get the correct measurements,

164
00:08:59.670 --> 00:09:04.590
or cardiac MRI is the other consideration.

165
00:09:04.590 --> 00:09:08.790
And management, these athletes are gonna go back to play.

166
00:09:08.790 --> 00:09:09.623
Okay?

167
00:09:09.623 --> 00:09:13.110
There is no indication that athletes should be withheld.

168
00:09:13.110 --> 00:09:14.400
They need to be withheld

169
00:09:14.400 --> 00:09:16.290
while they're getting a full evaluation.

170
00:09:16.290 --> 00:09:19.350
If the athlete wants to go back to play,

171
00:09:19.350 --> 00:09:23.220
they can safely go back to play with treatment,

172
00:09:23.220 --> 00:09:25.770
and first line treatment's beta blocker

173
00:09:25.770 --> 00:09:26.973
for these individuals.

174
00:09:29.130 --> 00:09:33.510
So the whole idea of, "I have hypertrophic cardiomyopathy.

175
00:09:33.510 --> 00:09:35.703
I shouldn't participate in sports,"

176
00:09:35.703 --> 00:09:37.833
throw that out the window.

177
00:09:40.410 --> 00:09:43.770
Once they're diagnosed and treated,

178
00:09:43.770 --> 00:09:47.400
athletes can safely be returned to sports.

179
00:09:47.400 --> 00:09:51.300
The key is making the diagnosis and getting them treatment.

180
00:09:51.300 --> 00:09:52.440
Commotio cordis.

181
00:09:52.440 --> 00:09:56.670
This is where I take a baseball or a lacrosse ball

182
00:09:56.670 --> 00:09:58.560
or some kind of blunt instrument

183
00:09:58.560 --> 00:10:00.704
that comes right over my precordium.

184
00:10:00.704 --> 00:10:05.130
It occurs during a vulnerable part of the cardiac cycle,

185
00:10:05.130 --> 00:10:07.110
and I go from ventricular tachycardia

186
00:10:07.110 --> 00:10:10.050
into ventricular fibrillation, and I arrest.

187
00:10:10.050 --> 00:10:12.585
This is your typical adolescent baseball pitcher

188
00:10:12.585 --> 00:10:16.350
who's on the mound and gets hit with a line drive

189
00:10:16.350 --> 00:10:19.200
and drops dead, so to speak.

190
00:10:19.200 --> 00:10:24.200
AEDs have turned this from a fatal injury or episode

191
00:10:26.548 --> 00:10:31.548
into one that is not common, but is not at all fatal.

192
00:10:32.670 --> 00:10:35.460
Because these are otherwise young, healthy individuals,

193
00:10:35.460 --> 00:10:38.880
we get the AED on them, they come right back.

194
00:10:38.880 --> 00:10:40.260
The key is timing.

195
00:10:40.260 --> 00:10:42.870
So like all things, getting the AED on them

196
00:10:42.870 --> 00:10:44.165
within three minutes.

197
00:10:44.165 --> 00:10:47.340
The very first description was written up

198
00:10:47.340 --> 00:10:51.420
in the New England Journal, I guess maybe 20 years ago now,

199
00:10:51.420 --> 00:10:54.420
and that adolescent baseball pitcher

200
00:10:54.420 --> 00:10:56.940
went back to pitching, right?

201
00:10:56.940 --> 00:10:59.580
So these are not common events.

202
00:10:59.580 --> 00:11:01.230
Chest protectors don't work,

203
00:11:01.230 --> 00:11:03.573
so that's another thing you wanna remember.

204
00:11:04.770 --> 00:11:07.473
We have to talk a little bit about SARS COVID-2.

205
00:11:08.520 --> 00:11:12.900
The incidence of mild care pericarditis in athletes

206
00:11:12.900 --> 00:11:15.150
is low overall.

207
00:11:15.150 --> 00:11:17.653
How do we evaluate this right now?

208
00:11:17.653 --> 00:11:22.350
If somebody has SARS COVID-2 and they're an athlete,

209
00:11:22.350 --> 00:11:24.753
particularly if they've had a fever,

210
00:11:26.190 --> 00:11:29.430
and they're out for more than three days,

211
00:11:29.430 --> 00:11:32.010
they're gonna get a full medical evaluation,

212
00:11:32.010 --> 00:11:37.010
they're gonna get an ECG, a troponin, and an echocardiogram.

213
00:11:37.410 --> 00:11:40.740
Those are normal. They can return to athletics.

214
00:11:40.740 --> 00:11:45.033
If they're abnormal, then that leads to further evaluation.

215
00:11:46.072 --> 00:11:48.510
The mRNA vaccine.

216
00:11:48.510 --> 00:11:51.297
Now again, we have to talk about vaccine

217
00:11:51.297 --> 00:11:54.000
and mild pericarditis.

218
00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:58.893
So who's at risk? I'm at risk with the mRNA vaccine.

219
00:12:00.090 --> 00:12:02.670
I'm a 20 to 30-year-old male,

220
00:12:02.670 --> 00:12:05.400
and I'm receiving my second vaccine.

221
00:12:05.400 --> 00:12:07.950
Now, we're probably getting very close

222
00:12:07.950 --> 00:12:10.395
to being outside this window,

223
00:12:10.395 --> 00:12:12.030
but we're gonna see it

224
00:12:12.030 --> 00:12:14.418
as we have younger individuals come up,

225
00:12:14.418 --> 00:12:17.100
individuals who've not been vaccinated.

226
00:12:17.100 --> 00:12:19.020
But the more people who are vaccinated,

227
00:12:19.020 --> 00:12:21.810
particularly if they've had two or three vaccines,

228
00:12:21.810 --> 00:12:24.750
they're outside this window of risk, okay?

229
00:12:24.750 --> 00:12:29.750
But that's my riskiest subgroup by far,

230
00:12:29.910 --> 00:12:31.920
by far my riskiest subgroup.

231
00:12:31.920 --> 00:12:34.110
20 to 30-year-old males

232
00:12:34.110 --> 00:12:38.430
who are receiving their second mRNA vaccine,

233
00:12:38.430 --> 00:12:39.930
they come in with shortness of breath

234
00:12:39.930 --> 00:12:44.363
or palpitations or chest pain, take them seriously, okay?

235
00:12:47.220 --> 00:12:51.193
Marfan syndrome, another autosomal dominant disease.

236
00:12:51.193 --> 00:12:55.140
You know, arm span greater than height,

237
00:12:55.140 --> 00:12:58.140
long, slender fingers, high arched palate,

238
00:12:58.140 --> 00:13:03.140
the pectus excavatum, anterior chest deformities,

239
00:13:04.020 --> 00:13:08.040
hyperextensible joints, these things.

240
00:13:08.040 --> 00:13:10.198
Complications in athletics,

241
00:13:10.198 --> 00:13:13.890
they have ascending aortic dilatation

242
00:13:13.890 --> 00:13:17.275
because collagen is involved.

243
00:13:17.275 --> 00:13:22.275
They also usually can have spontaneous pneumothoraces,

244
00:13:22.980 --> 00:13:25.590
so they're running down the field and boom,

245
00:13:25.590 --> 00:13:26.943
acutely short of breath.

246
00:13:27.973 --> 00:13:32.973
And so if you are suspicious of somebody having Marfan's,

247
00:13:33.776 --> 00:13:37.435
your physical exam, and I would add to that,

248
00:13:37.435 --> 00:13:42.120
you're gonna just gonna go to www.marfan.org,

249
00:13:42.120 --> 00:13:44.880
and you're gonna go to the systemic calculator,

250
00:13:44.880 --> 00:13:46.815
and you're gonna plug in the findings.

251
00:13:46.815 --> 00:13:49.320
And if you get a score of 7 or greater

252
00:13:49.320 --> 00:13:51.720
then they probably have Marfan's.

253
00:13:51.720 --> 00:13:54.090
Now I can consider genetic testing.

254
00:13:54.090 --> 00:13:57.720
We're still working on that, so it's not streamlined.

255
00:13:57.720 --> 00:14:02.550
But then I want to proceed with an echocardiogram

256
00:14:02.550 --> 00:14:05.730
and a slit lamp exam, okay?

257
00:14:05.730 --> 00:14:08.280
Those would be the next two tests.

258
00:14:08.280 --> 00:14:13.023
Infectious mononucleosis. The risk here is splenic rupture.

259
00:14:13.860 --> 00:14:16.730
I can develop hepatosplenomegaly,

260
00:14:16.730 --> 00:14:20.120
but we're usually focused on the splenomegaly

261
00:14:20.120 --> 00:14:22.080
that can occur with it.

262
00:14:22.080 --> 00:14:27.080
So as a general rule, my athlete who has infectious mono,

263
00:14:28.890 --> 00:14:33.239
they do not return to exercise or activity

264
00:14:33.239 --> 00:14:36.780
for 21 days post-diagnosis,

265
00:14:36.780 --> 00:14:39.735
and then they have to feel well enough to go back.

266
00:14:39.735 --> 00:14:43.320
If I have splenomegaly on exam,

267
00:14:43.320 --> 00:14:46.770
then they'll be continued to be held out

268
00:14:46.770 --> 00:14:49.140
until that splenomegaly resolves.

269
00:14:49.140 --> 00:14:50.973
Another Choosing Wisely,

270
00:14:52.320 --> 00:14:56.160
avoid ordering an abdominal ultrasound routinely in athletes

271
00:14:56.160 --> 00:14:57.390
with infectious mono.

272
00:14:57.390 --> 00:15:00.510
You're trying to assess for hepatosplenomegaly.

273
00:15:00.510 --> 00:15:02.460
Do it by physical exam.

274
00:15:02.460 --> 00:15:06.780
The spleen is of variable sizes in variable people.

275
00:15:06.780 --> 00:15:11.250
It's more related to my height than it is to my age,

276
00:15:11.250 --> 00:15:14.040
so there's no real norm.

277
00:15:14.040 --> 00:15:19.040
13 centimeters is the length that radiologists call,

278
00:15:19.920 --> 00:15:22.291
13 centimeters less, it's normal.

279
00:15:22.291 --> 00:15:25.950
Greater than 13 centimeters, it's enlarged.

280
00:15:25.950 --> 00:15:29.930
Well, again, I take asymptomatic individuals

281
00:15:29.930 --> 00:15:34.930
who are 6' or 6'5" and taller and measure 'em,

282
00:15:35.190 --> 00:15:38.340
and some of 'em have 20-centimeter spleens.

283
00:15:38.340 --> 00:15:40.680
They're completely fine, completely normal.

284
00:15:40.680 --> 00:15:45.192
So again, there's lots of variables that go into this,

285
00:15:45.192 --> 00:15:49.563
so we generally avoid that imaging.

286
00:15:50.460 --> 00:15:51.873
Okay, our next question.

287
00:15:52.860 --> 00:15:55.530
You're the team physician at an early preseason practice

288
00:15:55.530 --> 00:15:57.900
when a 17-year-old male stumbles off the field

289
00:15:57.900 --> 00:15:59.160
late in practice.

290
00:15:59.160 --> 00:16:00.900
He's an overweight lineman.

291
00:16:00.900 --> 00:16:03.467
He appears fatigued and he's sweating profusely.

292
00:16:03.467 --> 00:16:06.630
He's clumsy and mumbling incoherently.

293
00:16:06.630 --> 00:16:08.400
The trainer takes an oral temperature,

294
00:16:08.400 --> 00:16:11.160
which is 102.1 degrees Fahrenheit.

295
00:16:11.160 --> 00:16:12.690
The defining characteristic

296
00:16:12.690 --> 00:16:16.560
distinguishing between heat exhaustion and heat stroke

297
00:16:16.560 --> 00:16:17.943
is which of the following?

298
00:16:21.300 --> 00:16:24.270
Absence of sweating, mental status changes,

299
00:16:24.270 --> 00:16:26.332
presence of profuse sweating,

300
00:16:26.332 --> 00:16:30.093
or an oral temperature greater than 102 degrees.

301
00:16:35.580 --> 00:16:36.810
Okay, terrific.

302
00:16:36.810 --> 00:16:40.410
So mental status changes are the defining characteristic.

303
00:16:40.410 --> 00:16:44.820
So we see this as a spectrum illness, heat illness, right?

304
00:16:44.820 --> 00:16:47.370
I can go from heat cramps or heat syncope

305
00:16:47.370 --> 00:16:50.640
to heat exhaustion to heat stroke,

306
00:16:50.640 --> 00:16:52.530
and it's really the mental status changes

307
00:16:52.530 --> 00:16:55.530
that define the heat stroke,

308
00:16:55.530 --> 00:16:58.590
that part of the CNS dysfunction.

309
00:16:58.590 --> 00:17:00.600
And so you have your risk factors.

310
00:17:00.600 --> 00:17:02.220
Those who are unacclimated.

311
00:17:02.220 --> 00:17:05.100
I'm wearing a lot of clothing during practice,

312
00:17:05.100 --> 00:17:09.570
it's particularly hot out, I'm overweight.

313
00:17:09.570 --> 00:17:12.690
I may be trying to lose weight,

314
00:17:12.690 --> 00:17:16.350
so I'm using laxatives or diuretics.

315
00:17:16.350 --> 00:17:18.660
I may be using anticholinergics

316
00:17:18.660 --> 00:17:22.440
because I have allergies, et cetera.

317
00:17:22.440 --> 00:17:25.350
So I have all of these different medications

318
00:17:25.350 --> 00:17:27.930
that can also place me at risk.

319
00:17:27.930 --> 00:17:29.910
When you get your temperature,

320
00:17:29.910 --> 00:17:33.600
you need to get a rectal temperature, okay?

321
00:17:33.600 --> 00:17:35.610
Rectal temperature.

322
00:17:35.610 --> 00:17:39.180
And when you're gonna cool an individual with this,

323
00:17:39.180 --> 00:17:41.280
you're gonna cool 'em however you can.

324
00:17:41.280 --> 00:17:44.613
In real life, you cool 'em as you can.

325
00:17:45.720 --> 00:17:47.790
Put cold towels on 'em, strip 'em down,

326
00:17:47.790 --> 00:17:49.500
throw ice packs on 'em.

327
00:17:49.500 --> 00:17:52.740
Whatever you have available, you use.

328
00:17:52.740 --> 00:17:57.330
But when you have a choice between lots of cooling methods

329
00:17:57.330 --> 00:17:59.763
and ice water immersion, what do you do?

330
00:18:00.750 --> 00:18:05.750
Ice water immersion is your best cooling technique.

331
00:18:06.300 --> 00:18:07.563
Okay, our next question.

332
00:18:08.730 --> 00:18:10.320
Which of the following statements is true

333
00:18:10.320 --> 00:18:13.200
regarding sports related concussion?

334
00:18:13.200 --> 00:18:15.130
A, physical activity is recommended

335
00:18:17.646 --> 00:18:21.154
24 to 48 hours post-concussion;

336
00:18:21.154 --> 00:18:23.340
B, return to sports can occur

337
00:18:23.340 --> 00:18:27.030
prior to return to baseline academics;

338
00:18:27.030 --> 00:18:30.060
C, physical rest is recommended until all symptoms

339
00:18:30.060 --> 00:18:33.270
of the sports related concussion have resolved;

340
00:18:33.270 --> 00:18:35.160
or D, the overall duration

341
00:18:35.160 --> 00:18:38.070
of sports related concussion symptoms is the same

342
00:18:38.070 --> 00:18:41.043
in children, adolescents, and young adults.

343
00:18:45.926 --> 00:18:50.926
Okay, so the correct answer is A. A.

344
00:18:51.060 --> 00:18:53.910
This has changed within the last couple of years,

345
00:18:53.910 --> 00:18:57.900
so let's cover the highlights of what has changed.

346
00:18:57.900 --> 00:19:02.318
Here are my risks, right? Certain sports put me at risk.

347
00:19:02.318 --> 00:19:05.520
Competition as opposed to practice.

348
00:19:05.520 --> 00:19:08.130
I have a higher risk in competition.

349
00:19:08.130 --> 00:19:12.600
If I'm female, I'm at higher risk for having a concussion.

350
00:19:12.600 --> 00:19:14.455
If I've had one concussion,

351
00:19:14.455 --> 00:19:16.650
I'm at higher risk for the second.

352
00:19:16.650 --> 00:19:17.483
If I've had two,

353
00:19:17.483 --> 00:19:20.700
I'm at higher risk for the third, et cetera.

354
00:19:20.700 --> 00:19:24.870
And then if I'm involved in an activity or a sport

355
00:19:24.870 --> 00:19:26.700
where I have player to player contact,

356
00:19:26.700 --> 00:19:29.220
because that's where most concussions occur.

357
00:19:29.220 --> 00:19:32.460
70% occur because of player to player contact,

358
00:19:32.460 --> 00:19:36.720
not player to the environment,

359
00:19:36.720 --> 00:19:40.860
some inanimate object, all right?

360
00:19:40.860 --> 00:19:44.834
The most common symptom they're gonna have is headache.

361
00:19:44.834 --> 00:19:48.270
Otherwise, to round out the top four,

362
00:19:48.270 --> 00:19:52.290
dizziness, confusion, poor concentration.

363
00:19:52.290 --> 00:19:54.783
Again, Choosing Wisely.

364
00:19:54.783 --> 00:19:59.783
Do not image the heads of these individuals

365
00:19:59.846 --> 00:20:02.580
unless they're having focal

366
00:20:02.580 --> 00:20:05.520
or progressive neurologic dysfunction.

367
00:20:05.520 --> 00:20:07.309
Just because my head hurts,

368
00:20:07.309 --> 00:20:12.309
just because I still get dizzy when I'm up walking around,

369
00:20:13.230 --> 00:20:16.508
just because light still bothers my eyes

370
00:20:16.508 --> 00:20:18.975
three weeks, four weeks,

371
00:20:18.975 --> 00:20:22.560
no, there's no reason to image.

372
00:20:22.560 --> 00:20:24.720
This is not a structural problem.

373
00:20:24.720 --> 00:20:26.820
This is a functional problem,

374
00:20:26.820 --> 00:20:28.288
and we don't have a way

375
00:20:28.288 --> 00:20:31.990
to readily identify the functional deficit

376
00:20:31.990 --> 00:20:34.113
outside of our history and exam.

377
00:20:35.387 --> 00:20:38.640
Okay, so you wanna pay attention

378
00:20:38.640 --> 00:20:41.970
to this Sport Concussion Assessment Tool.

379
00:20:41.970 --> 00:20:45.150
You don't have to use it. Again, it's available online.

380
00:20:45.150 --> 00:20:47.466
It's free to download and utilize.

381
00:20:47.466 --> 00:20:51.611
But you need to know that this is the very best instrument

382
00:20:51.611 --> 00:20:56.130
for the sideline evaluation of athletes, okay?

383
00:20:56.130 --> 00:20:58.860
The 6 just means it's Version 6,

384
00:20:58.860 --> 00:21:02.520
and it really hasn't changed very much from Version 1 on.

385
00:21:02.520 --> 00:21:04.347
There's a Child-SCAT(6),

386
00:21:05.640 --> 00:21:09.360
and that's used for children ages 5 to 12.

387
00:21:09.360 --> 00:21:14.093
The SCAT is for 13 and older, okay?

388
00:21:15.090 --> 00:21:17.070
Any athlete who has a concussion

389
00:21:17.070 --> 00:21:20.373
does not return to play that same day, period.

390
00:21:21.648 --> 00:21:26.648
And neuropsychological testing, like impact testing,

391
00:21:26.908 --> 00:21:30.300
is not diagnostic,

392
00:21:30.300 --> 00:21:35.300
it is adjunct in the management of concussion.

393
00:21:36.309 --> 00:21:39.807
Okay, so what about the management? What do we do?

394
00:21:39.807 --> 00:21:44.130
Well, we recommend physical and cognitive rest

395
00:21:44.130 --> 00:21:47.100
for the first 24, maybe 48 hours.

396
00:21:47.100 --> 00:21:49.230
That's it, max.

397
00:21:49.230 --> 00:21:50.460
Then we follow up,

398
00:21:50.460 --> 00:21:54.653
and we found that if we prescribe light activity

399
00:21:54.653 --> 00:21:59.653
in that 24 to 48-hour timeframe, they do better.

400
00:22:00.510 --> 00:22:03.000
They recover faster, okay?

401
00:22:03.000 --> 00:22:06.808
So full rest, as we were doing before,

402
00:22:06.808 --> 00:22:10.983
actually, while it might've made sense,

403
00:22:12.230 --> 00:22:15.420
the symptoms were prolonged with it,

404
00:22:15.420 --> 00:22:18.690
and they recover faster if we bring 'em back to activity.

405
00:22:18.690 --> 00:22:20.250
That does not mean I bring 'em back

406
00:22:20.250 --> 00:22:22.650
to sport and contact activity,

407
00:22:22.650 --> 00:22:25.080
but that means I get 'em out and I get 'em bike riding,

408
00:22:25.080 --> 00:22:26.460
or I get 'em walking,

409
00:22:26.460 --> 00:22:28.890
or I get 'em out shooting some baskets.

410
00:22:28.890 --> 00:22:33.720
You know, they're doing things that help them physically,

411
00:22:33.720 --> 00:22:36.270
that do not exacerbate their symptoms.

412
00:22:36.270 --> 00:22:37.740
That's what we're trying to do.

413
00:22:37.740 --> 00:22:42.270
Again, this all has happened in the last couple years,

414
00:22:42.270 --> 00:22:43.230
and it's already made it

415
00:22:43.230 --> 00:22:46.170
to the Choosing Wisely campaign, okay,

416
00:22:46.170 --> 00:22:49.080
to recommend early physical activity

417
00:22:49.080 --> 00:22:51.393
and cognitive activity as tolerated.

418
00:22:53.370 --> 00:22:56.400
Individuals have to return to their academic baseline

419
00:22:56.400 --> 00:23:00.388
before they return to sport, okay?

420
00:23:00.388 --> 00:23:03.480
That's a call both from our academy

421
00:23:03.480 --> 00:23:06.540
and the American Academy of Pediatrics.

422
00:23:06.540 --> 00:23:08.190
And then once they're ready,

423
00:23:08.190 --> 00:23:10.408
once they've returned to their academic baseline,

424
00:23:10.408 --> 00:23:12.420
then we start a process

425
00:23:12.420 --> 00:23:14.730
of graded return to sport after that.

426
00:23:14.730 --> 00:23:18.326
And we'll sort of demonstrate that in a couple of slides.

427
00:23:18.326 --> 00:23:21.810
Most all athletes are gonna have symptom resolution

428
00:23:21.810 --> 00:23:24.600
by 7 to 10 days post-injury,

429
00:23:24.600 --> 00:23:26.220
and I gave you some risk factors

430
00:23:26.220 --> 00:23:29.100
for those who might have prolonged symptoms.

431
00:23:29.100 --> 00:23:32.220
And recognize that younger children take longer.

432
00:23:32.220 --> 00:23:35.370
So we give younger children, 5 to 12 years of age,

433
00:23:35.370 --> 00:23:37.524
four weeks to resolve,

434
00:23:37.524 --> 00:23:42.524
where we give 13 and older three weeks to resolve

435
00:23:42.660 --> 00:23:45.946
before we start calling their symptoms prolonged.

436
00:23:45.946 --> 00:23:49.029
Okay, so this is what it really looks like.

437
00:23:49.029 --> 00:23:52.170
You have your time on the x-axis.

438
00:23:52.170 --> 00:23:54.330
I sustain a sports related concussion.

439
00:23:54.330 --> 00:23:55.830
I have this burst of symptoms,

440
00:23:55.830 --> 00:23:58.713
headache, dizziness, confusion,

441
00:24:00.000 --> 00:24:04.860
and I get this burst, and then they start improving.

442
00:24:04.860 --> 00:24:06.660
Within 24 to 48 hours,

443
00:24:06.660 --> 00:24:09.090
I'm prescribing light physical activity,

444
00:24:09.090 --> 00:24:12.153
which helps the symptoms improve more.

445
00:24:13.770 --> 00:24:16.200
My next focus is on getting 'em back

446
00:24:16.200 --> 00:24:18.810
to their academic baseline and getting 'em back to school.

447
00:24:18.810 --> 00:24:23.810
We call this Return to Learning. So I incorporate this.

448
00:24:23.820 --> 00:24:25.890
Once I have achieved this

449
00:24:25.890 --> 00:24:28.830
and gotten them back to their academic baseline,

450
00:24:28.830 --> 00:24:31.340
and their symptoms are continuing to improve,

451
00:24:31.340 --> 00:24:35.160
now I can talk about returning to sport.

452
00:24:35.160 --> 00:24:36.780
And what does that look like?

453
00:24:36.780 --> 00:24:40.350
Well, it looks like now I have a stepwise progression.

454
00:24:40.350 --> 00:24:45.060
Each day I allow them to do something a little bit more.

455
00:24:45.060 --> 00:24:47.160
And then the key point here

456
00:24:47.160 --> 00:24:50.520
is before they're gonna go back to full contact,

457
00:24:50.520 --> 00:24:53.040
they're coming to see you.

458
00:24:53.040 --> 00:24:57.060
You're gonna clear them to go back for full contact,

459
00:24:57.060 --> 00:24:59.940
and then if they do that, gameplay, right?

460
00:24:59.940 --> 00:25:02.820
But that's a key component in here,

461
00:25:02.820 --> 00:25:05.241
the medical evaluation that occurs

462
00:25:05.241 --> 00:25:08.583
prior to them going back to full contact.

463
00:25:10.620 --> 00:25:12.300
All right, eating disorders.

464
00:25:12.300 --> 00:25:15.946
You know, again, we have to mention, sadly,

465
00:25:15.946 --> 00:25:19.290
you know, they're much more common

466
00:25:19.290 --> 00:25:21.480
in the athletic population,

467
00:25:21.480 --> 00:25:26.480
and also common among males in this population.

468
00:25:27.300 --> 00:25:30.180
You have to really think about the comorbidities,

469
00:25:30.180 --> 00:25:33.960
mostly mental health comorbidities, but substance use,

470
00:25:33.960 --> 00:25:38.223
which is another big comorbidity in this population.

471
00:25:40.440 --> 00:25:43.530
Okay, now talking about some specific injuries.

472
00:25:43.530 --> 00:25:45.723
Anterior shoulder dislocation.

473
00:25:46.770 --> 00:25:48.466
70% of these are anterior,

474
00:25:48.466 --> 00:25:51.843
and virtually all of those are traumatic.

475
00:25:53.130 --> 00:25:56.610
You're gonna be asked, "Where do you reduce them?"

476
00:25:56.610 --> 00:25:59.070
I got a shoulder dislocation on the field.

477
00:25:59.070 --> 00:26:02.280
Where does it get reduced? It gets reduced on the field.

478
00:26:02.280 --> 00:26:03.960
You reduce it right then and there.

479
00:26:03.960 --> 00:26:05.735
I know I don't have X-ray.

480
00:26:05.735 --> 00:26:07.560
I know I don't feel like...

481
00:26:07.560 --> 00:26:08.673
How do I do this?

482
00:26:10.110 --> 00:26:10.943
The question is

483
00:26:10.943 --> 00:26:13.950
where do you reduce the shoulder dislocation?

484
00:26:13.950 --> 00:26:15.990
You reduce it on the field. Why?

485
00:26:15.990 --> 00:26:18.870
Because it's easier, because it saves me conscious sedation,

486
00:26:18.870 --> 00:26:21.210
because it saves me everything else

487
00:26:21.210 --> 00:26:24.612
that goes along with the conscious sedation, all the risks.

488
00:26:24.612 --> 00:26:29.160
I can reduce it immediately and easily on the field,

489
00:26:29.160 --> 00:26:30.480
and so I do that.

490
00:26:30.480 --> 00:26:33.810
Remember, you do a neurovascular exam of the upper extremity

491
00:26:33.810 --> 00:26:37.293
before and after, okay?

492
00:26:40.080 --> 00:26:42.420
Femoral acetabular impingement.

493
00:26:42.420 --> 00:26:44.610
This is another you should know about.

494
00:26:44.610 --> 00:26:48.213
This is relatively new in the last decade or so.

495
00:26:49.525 --> 00:26:53.389
The thing to really pay attention to here,

496
00:26:53.389 --> 00:26:57.030
this is not necessarily acquired.

497
00:26:57.030 --> 00:26:58.500
We don't know exactly,

498
00:26:58.500 --> 00:27:03.500
but there seems to be some hereditary component to this,

499
00:27:06.660 --> 00:27:11.660
which then might be exacerbated by specific activities.

500
00:27:11.760 --> 00:27:16.760
But we develop an abnormality of the femoral head

501
00:27:17.550 --> 00:27:19.197
and/or acetabulum,

502
00:27:19.197 --> 00:27:21.210
and those basically rub on each other

503
00:27:21.210 --> 00:27:22.683
and they can cause pain.

504
00:27:24.480 --> 00:27:27.150
The thing that's most important for you to know here

505
00:27:27.150 --> 00:27:32.150
is the FAdIR test: flexion, adduction, internal rotation,

506
00:27:32.910 --> 00:27:37.910
the most sensitive test for femoral acetabular impingement.

507
00:27:38.100 --> 00:27:41.160
It's not FABER, it's not figure of four.

508
00:27:41.160 --> 00:27:44.573
That's FADIR. This is FAdIR.

509
00:27:46.290 --> 00:27:49.493
That's FABER, this is FAdIR, okay?

510
00:27:51.333 --> 00:27:53.970
Flexion, abduction, internal rotation.

511
00:27:53.970 --> 00:27:55.650
If I'm really concerned about this,

512
00:27:55.650 --> 00:27:58.032
and I think I have an athlete who has it,

513
00:27:58.032 --> 00:28:01.051
I do a lidocaine injection into the hip

514
00:28:01.051 --> 00:28:03.060
and I see how they do.

515
00:28:03.060 --> 00:28:05.677
And if all their symptoms go away and they're fine,

516
00:28:05.677 --> 00:28:07.560
you're essentially diagnostic,

517
00:28:07.560 --> 00:28:10.230
then you can go on to imaging at that point in time,

518
00:28:10.230 --> 00:28:11.373
which would be an MRI.

519
00:28:12.510 --> 00:28:14.634
Okay, next question.

520
00:28:14.634 --> 00:28:17.670
You've been invited to present a grand rounds lecture

521
00:28:17.670 --> 00:28:19.590
on "Sports Injuries in High School Athletes."

522
00:28:19.590 --> 00:28:21.300
Which of the following statements

523
00:28:21.300 --> 00:28:23.670
would you include in your talk?

524
00:28:23.670 --> 00:28:27.573
So which of the following statements is true?

525
00:28:33.420 --> 00:28:35.490
Okay, so we're split a little bit

526
00:28:35.490 --> 00:28:38.975
between football having the highest injury rate

527
00:28:38.975 --> 00:28:43.975
and the knee being the most commonly injured body part.

528
00:28:44.340 --> 00:28:48.153
So let's look at this. A is the correct answer.

529
00:28:49.080 --> 00:28:52.053
So we're gonna look at some of this data real fast.

530
00:28:54.720 --> 00:28:58.410
This has been true. It is true.

531
00:28:58.410 --> 00:29:03.410
I've stopped taking the data this next year in 2023-24.

532
00:29:03.630 --> 00:29:05.220
We'll start compiling the data

533
00:29:05.220 --> 00:29:09.270
because COVID really messed up the data.

534
00:29:09.270 --> 00:29:12.120
Board's never gonna test you on messed up data.

535
00:29:12.120 --> 00:29:14.598
They're testing you on common things,

536
00:29:14.598 --> 00:29:17.040
being commonist if you will.

537
00:29:17.040 --> 00:29:19.800
So football has the highest injury rate.

538
00:29:19.800 --> 00:29:22.428
Someone or many of you're gonna ask me about cheer.

539
00:29:22.428 --> 00:29:27.210
Cheerleading has the highest catastrophic injury rate,

540
00:29:27.210 --> 00:29:30.912
right, subsequent paralysis, death,

541
00:29:30.912 --> 00:29:34.770
severe head injury, spine injury,

542
00:29:34.770 --> 00:29:36.660
but it doesn't have the highest injury rate.

543
00:29:36.660 --> 00:29:39.033
It's the highest catastrophic injury rate.

544
00:29:39.960 --> 00:29:43.350
When I look at competition or practice,

545
00:29:43.350 --> 00:29:45.630
more of my injuries occur in competition.

546
00:29:45.630 --> 00:29:50.630
It's uncontrolled, or less controlled than is practice.

547
00:29:51.030 --> 00:29:54.360
When I look at the most commonly injured body parts,

548
00:29:54.360 --> 00:29:56.910
head and face, far and away,

549
00:29:56.910 --> 00:30:01.910
and that includes concussion, followed by ankle.

550
00:30:01.950 --> 00:30:06.950
Makes sense. And then knee comes in third.

551
00:30:08.648 --> 00:30:10.500
You need to know this.

552
00:30:10.500 --> 00:30:12.540
The most commonly injured knee structure,

553
00:30:12.540 --> 00:30:14.911
and I don't care how they ask it of you,

554
00:30:14.911 --> 00:30:19.911
high school sport, college sport, intramural sport,

555
00:30:20.010 --> 00:30:23.250
whatever it might be, the answer is the MCL.

556
00:30:23.250 --> 00:30:26.970
It's not the ACL, it is the medial collateral ligament

557
00:30:26.970 --> 00:30:30.933
is the most commonly injured knee structure.

558
00:30:31.950 --> 00:30:33.273
Okay, our next question.

559
00:30:34.440 --> 00:30:37.530
In a 20-year-old otherwise healthy athlete,

560
00:30:37.530 --> 00:30:41.670
which physical exam test is the most sensitive maneuver

561
00:30:41.670 --> 00:30:43.713
for the corresponding knee injury?

562
00:30:44.970 --> 00:30:49.773
Is it A, the Thessaly test for a meniscal tear;

563
00:30:50.610 --> 00:30:54.633
the anterior drawer test for the anterior cruciate ligament;

564
00:30:55.710 --> 00:30:59.051
a McMurray test for the meniscal tear;

565
00:30:59.051 --> 00:31:02.973
or a valgus stress test for the lateral collateral ligament?

566
00:31:08.670 --> 00:31:11.640
So we're split on this, and we're gonna go over these.

567
00:31:11.640 --> 00:31:13.697
I somewhat anticipated that.

568
00:31:13.697 --> 00:31:16.020
It's the Thessaly test, far and away.

569
00:31:16.020 --> 00:31:17.770
And if you don't know how to do it,

570
00:31:19.674 --> 00:31:22.740
you should learn how to do it, okay?

571
00:31:22.740 --> 00:31:25.290
What we're gonna do is just cover these.

572
00:31:25.290 --> 00:31:29.190
The most sensitive test for the ACL,

573
00:31:29.190 --> 00:31:31.710
you need to know this, they will ask you this.

574
00:31:31.710 --> 00:31:36.092
It is the Lachman maneuver or the Lachman test.

575
00:31:36.092 --> 00:31:38.400
For the posterior cruciate ligament,

576
00:31:38.400 --> 00:31:41.790
it's the posterior drawer test.

577
00:31:41.790 --> 00:31:43.827
For the medial collateral ligament,

578
00:31:43.827 --> 00:31:47.160
it's the valgus stress test.

579
00:31:47.160 --> 00:31:50.100
That's testing the medial collateral ligament.

580
00:31:50.100 --> 00:31:53.028
Remember, that's the most commonly injured knee ligament

581
00:31:53.028 --> 00:31:55.011
in sports.

582
00:31:55.011 --> 00:31:58.200
For a meniscal tear, it's a Thessaly test,

583
00:31:58.200 --> 00:32:01.170
and it can either be a single-legged Thessaly test

584
00:32:01.170 --> 00:32:03.990
or a double-legged Thessaly test.

585
00:32:03.990 --> 00:32:08.760
But basically I'm on bent knees about 20 to 30 degrees

586
00:32:08.760 --> 00:32:13.760
and I need to pivot or swing on my knees three times, right?

587
00:32:15.450 --> 00:32:17.760
Sort of a dance we do with the athlete,

588
00:32:17.760 --> 00:32:20.610
and they should have pain in the area of the knee

589
00:32:20.610 --> 00:32:22.590
where the meniscal tear occurred,

590
00:32:22.590 --> 00:32:25.650
or where I suspect the meniscal tear is.

591
00:32:25.650 --> 00:32:27.510
Okay, next question.

592
00:32:27.510 --> 00:32:29.610
Which of the following statements is true

593
00:32:29.610 --> 00:32:31.983
regarding ACL injuries?

594
00:32:33.960 --> 00:32:36.330
A, prevention programs are ineffective

595
00:32:36.330 --> 00:32:38.313
at reducing ACL injury;

596
00:32:39.270 --> 00:32:42.510
B, bracing is effective in the secondary prevention

597
00:32:42.510 --> 00:32:43.803
of ACL injury;

598
00:32:44.640 --> 00:32:47.310
C, in high school sports, football has the highest rate

599
00:32:47.310 --> 00:32:48.723
of ACL injury;

600
00:32:49.560 --> 00:32:51.900
or D, surgical repair of an ACL tear

601
00:32:51.900 --> 00:32:55.143
results in lower rates of knee osteoarthritis.

602
00:33:01.200 --> 00:33:03.960
Okay, what did we pick? Okay, excellent.

603
00:33:03.960 --> 00:33:07.672
So C is the correct answer,

604
00:33:07.672 --> 00:33:11.760
and we're just gonna cover this stuff in one slide, right?

605
00:33:11.760 --> 00:33:15.090
Most ACL injuries are non-contact injuries,

606
00:33:15.090 --> 00:33:17.670
non-contact injuries.

607
00:33:17.670 --> 00:33:19.740
In high school sports, it's football.

608
00:33:19.740 --> 00:33:22.230
In collegiate sports, it's women's soccer

609
00:33:22.230 --> 00:33:24.753
that have the highest rates of ACL injury.

610
00:33:27.250 --> 00:33:32.250
Neuromuscular training programs or preparticipation training

611
00:33:33.092 --> 00:33:38.092
is effective to reduce the rates of ACL injury

612
00:33:38.160 --> 00:33:40.770
in female athletes, for sure.

613
00:33:40.770 --> 00:33:45.044
Maybe in male, but the data's been a little conflicting

614
00:33:45.044 --> 00:33:47.190
in male athletes.

615
00:33:47.190 --> 00:33:49.320
Surgical repair's treatment of choice

616
00:33:49.320 --> 00:33:51.840
if I have an unstable knee.

617
00:33:51.840 --> 00:33:55.226
Knee bracing is ineffective in preventing ACL

618
00:33:55.226 --> 00:33:59.040
either in the primary setting or the secondary setting.

619
00:33:59.040 --> 00:34:02.160
That's why we don't use ACL braces anymore.

620
00:34:02.160 --> 00:34:05.010
They've gone by the wayside, okay?

621
00:34:05.010 --> 00:34:06.660
What you see a lot of times

622
00:34:06.660 --> 00:34:09.543
are hinged knee braces on athletes,

623
00:34:10.680 --> 00:34:13.563
but they don't have anything to do with the ACL.

624
00:34:14.550 --> 00:34:17.910
They're primarily there for other reasons,

625
00:34:17.910 --> 00:34:21.120
and in your football linemen on Saturdays,

626
00:34:21.120 --> 00:34:23.130
they're there to protect the MCL,

627
00:34:23.130 --> 00:34:26.670
because that's the most commonly injured knee ligament.

628
00:34:26.670 --> 00:34:29.850
And then whether or not I develop osteoarthritis

629
00:34:29.850 --> 00:34:30.683
in the knee,

630
00:34:30.683 --> 00:34:33.523
this is important to be able to share with your patients.

631
00:34:33.523 --> 00:34:37.080
I tore the ACL, damage has been done.

632
00:34:37.080 --> 00:34:41.000
I'm at the same risk whether I get my ACL repaired or not.

633
00:34:41.000 --> 00:34:44.400
I'm gonna eventually develop osteoarthritis in the knee.

634
00:34:44.400 --> 00:34:47.370
The question will be how quickly is that going to occur.

635
00:34:47.370 --> 00:34:50.190
The answer is, it'll be faster

636
00:34:50.190 --> 00:34:54.496
in my athlete who had an ACL tear than it will be in me,

637
00:34:54.496 --> 00:34:58.920
because I haven't had an ACL tear, all right?

638
00:34:58.920 --> 00:35:02.880
So these are sort of vagaries that we speak in,

639
00:35:02.880 --> 00:35:05.460
but that's what we convey to them.

640
00:35:05.460 --> 00:35:08.340
Okay, this should be our last question.

641
00:35:08.340 --> 00:35:11.427
A 26-year-old male suffers an inversion ankle injury

642
00:35:11.427 --> 00:35:14.430
and ambulates to the ED for evaluation.

643
00:35:14.430 --> 00:35:16.260
You find lateral ankle swelling

644
00:35:16.260 --> 00:35:19.139
and tenderness over the anterior distal fibula.

645
00:35:19.139 --> 00:35:23.180
The next best course of action includes...

646
00:35:24.780 --> 00:35:27.480
Is it A, avoidance of the use of ankle bracing

647
00:35:27.480 --> 00:35:29.490
after his injury resolves;

648
00:35:29.490 --> 00:35:32.758
B, recommendations for early range of motion of the ankle;

649
00:35:32.758 --> 00:35:35.580
C, avoidance of the use of nonsteroidals;

650
00:35:35.580 --> 00:35:37.653
or D, radiographs of the ankle?

651
00:35:43.380 --> 00:35:44.400
Okay, excellent.

652
00:35:44.400 --> 00:35:46.710
So recommendation for early range of motion.

653
00:35:46.710 --> 00:35:50.790
So ankle sprains, remember most common are lateral,

654
00:35:50.790 --> 00:35:54.330
but the second most common are your high ankle sprains

655
00:35:54.330 --> 00:35:56.163
or your syndesmotic sprains.

656
00:35:57.540 --> 00:35:59.760
That's your second most common.

657
00:35:59.760 --> 00:36:03.090
Early range of motion improves recovery.

658
00:36:03.090 --> 00:36:04.710
Nonsteroidals are helpful.

659
00:36:04.710 --> 00:36:07.720
They can reduce not only my pain,

660
00:36:07.720 --> 00:36:10.590
but reduce my return to play time

661
00:36:10.590 --> 00:36:13.462
so that I can get back to play more quickly.

662
00:36:13.462 --> 00:36:18.462
And unlike the ACL, ankle bracing is effective

663
00:36:18.641 --> 00:36:22.200
in both the primary and secondary prevention

664
00:36:22.200 --> 00:36:23.343
of ankle sprains.

665
00:36:24.360 --> 00:36:25.862
Someone's gonna ask me,

666
00:36:25.862 --> 00:36:28.764
well, should we prescribe ankle braces

667
00:36:28.764 --> 00:36:32.370
to all of our athletes before they go out and play soccer

668
00:36:32.370 --> 00:36:37.257
or play field hockey or football?

669
00:36:37.257 --> 00:36:40.140
And the answer is, good luck, right?

670
00:36:40.140 --> 00:36:41.982
If I haven't had an ankle sprain,

671
00:36:41.982 --> 00:36:45.510
do I really want to be wearing something?

672
00:36:45.510 --> 00:36:47.700
And the answer is, I would tell you in my experience,

673
00:36:47.700 --> 00:36:50.373
the answer is almost universally no.

674
00:36:51.360 --> 00:36:54.540
Some of 'em will get taped in the training room.

675
00:36:54.540 --> 00:36:56.940
That's helpful, you know?

676
00:36:56.940 --> 00:36:59.940
That's gonna provide some benefit to them.

677
00:36:59.940 --> 00:37:01.639
After they've had a sprain,

678
00:37:01.639 --> 00:37:04.950
it's even difficult to get them to wear something

679
00:37:04.950 --> 00:37:06.960
for secondary prevention,

680
00:37:06.960 --> 00:37:10.200
because they like the way the cleat fits on their foot,

681
00:37:10.200 --> 00:37:12.570
they like the way their shoe fits on their foot.

682
00:37:12.570 --> 00:37:16.923
They don't like the inhibition that a brace affords them.

683
00:37:18.360 --> 00:37:19.440
Okay, and again,

684
00:37:19.440 --> 00:37:24.319
you're seeing the Ottawa Ankle Rules again, okay,

685
00:37:24.319 --> 00:37:28.530
because you need to know these, and I think most of you do.

686
00:37:28.530 --> 00:37:30.245
And the last thing I want to touch on here

687
00:37:30.245 --> 00:37:32.490
in this sports medicine talk

688
00:37:32.490 --> 00:37:34.770
is these impingement neuropathies.

689
00:37:34.770 --> 00:37:35.730
Now, remember we said

690
00:37:35.730 --> 00:37:39.783
the most common upper extremity impingement neuropathy is?

691
00:37:42.930 --> 00:37:46.320
Carpal tunnel syndrome is the most common.

692
00:37:46.320 --> 00:37:49.710
But in certain athletes, they're at high risk

693
00:37:49.710 --> 00:37:52.110
for other entrapment neuropathies.

694
00:37:52.110 --> 00:37:56.550
So if I'm a cyclist, I can develop handlebar neuropathy,

695
00:37:56.550 --> 00:38:01.230
and that's the ulnar nerve at Guyan's canal, okay?

696
00:38:01.230 --> 00:38:04.848
Because my hands are resting on the handlebars,

697
00:38:04.848 --> 00:38:08.970
and I get some impingement right there.

698
00:38:08.970 --> 00:38:10.110
And so what happens?

699
00:38:10.110 --> 00:38:12.810
I get numbness of my fifth finger

700
00:38:12.810 --> 00:38:16.783
and the ulnar aspect of my ring finger on the palmar side.

701
00:38:16.783 --> 00:38:21.783
If I'm a thrower, typically baseball pitchers,

702
00:38:22.161 --> 00:38:25.410
I can develop an ulnar neuropathy,

703
00:38:25.410 --> 00:38:29.580
but I get numbness on the dorsal aspect of my fifth digit

704
00:38:29.580 --> 00:38:32.846
and the ulnar aspect of my fourth digit,

705
00:38:32.846 --> 00:38:35.040
and that's cubital tunnel syndrome,

706
00:38:35.040 --> 00:38:37.473
ulnar nerve at the elbow.

707
00:38:39.510 --> 00:38:44.003
And then if I'm a cyclist and my seat's a little too narrow,

708
00:38:44.003 --> 00:38:48.387
I can develop a pudendal neuropathy

709
00:38:49.770 --> 00:38:52.710
or a cyclist's neuropathy.

710
00:38:52.710 --> 00:38:56.580
And what I want to do, and this has been asked before,

711
00:38:56.580 --> 00:39:01.260
so what I want to do is I wanna widen out that seat, okay?

712
00:39:01.260 --> 00:39:05.070
Take some of the pressure off of the pudendal nerve.

713
00:39:05.070 --> 00:39:08.220
And then peroneal neuropathy is strictly those

714
00:39:08.220 --> 00:39:10.290
who are associated with some kind of trauma.

715
00:39:10.290 --> 00:39:12.150
They get hit on the outer aspect

716
00:39:12.150 --> 00:39:13.860
or the lateral aspect of the knee,

717
00:39:13.860 --> 00:39:16.620
or just below the knee by the fibular head,

718
00:39:16.620 --> 00:39:20.662
and they can develop a peroneal neuropathy, all right?

719
00:39:20.662 --> 00:39:22.620
That's it for sports medicine.

720
00:39:22.620 --> 00:39:24.045
Thank you very much.

721
00:39:24.045 --> 00:39:25.971
(attendees clapping)

722
00:39:25.971 --> 00:39:28.554
(chiming tone)

